The '''Astrological Association''' is a British astrological organisation. The Astrological Association of Great Britain (AA) was formed in London on the 21st June 1958.<ref name="astrologicalassociation.com">[http://astrologicalassociation.com/pages/about/foundation.php History of the Astrological Association]</ref> Its founding members, notably [[John Addey (astrologer)|John Addey]] and [[Roy Firebrace]], were members of the Astrological Lodge of the Thesosophical Society.<ref>Lewis, James R, ''The astrology book: the encyclopedia of heavenly influences'', p.71. Visible Ink Press, 2003. {{ISBN|978-1-57859-144-2}}.</ref> John Addey later become President of the AA.<ref name=campion>[[Nicholas Campion|Campion, Nicholas]], ''A History of Western Astrology, Vol II: The Medieval and Modern Worlds'', pp. 277-8. Continuum, 2009, {{ISBN|978-1-4411-8129-9}}</ref> The AA produces three publications - the ''Astrological Journal'', published six times a year, ''Correlation'', published biannually, and the ''Medical Astrology Newsletter''. In 2002 the AA said their membership was "something over a thousand".<ref name=campion />
In 2013 the organisation was awarded charity status and the name was legally changed to 'The Astrological Association'.<ref>[http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithoutPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1152804&SubsidiaryNumber=0 Charity no. 1152804]</ref>
==Aims and Objectives== The aims of the Astrological Association are: the advancement of education of the public by the critical study of astrology in all its branches; to encourage and draw together all students of astrology; to enlarge and integrate the knowledge of astrology; to co-ordinate and publish results as desirable and generally work for the more widespread understanding of astrology.<ref name="astrologicalassociation.com"/>
It holds events and seminars throughout the year, along with an annual conference that draws astrologers from all over the world.
