The '''Irano-Afghan race''' (also known as the '''Iranid race''') is an obsolete term for a physical type most common among populations native to the [[Iranian plateau]].<ref>S. M. Garn, ''Human races'', Thomas, 1971, 3rd ed., University of Michigan, p. 196</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2Fx6pzonsCIC&pg=PA132 Race and Racism: An Introduction] [https://www.amazon.com/Race-Racism-Introduction-Carolyn-Fluehr-Lobban/dp/0759107955# (see also)] by Carolyn Fluehr-Lobban, Pages 127–133, Publication Date: December 8, 2005, {{ISBN|0759107955}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theapricity.com/snpa/racesofeurope.htm The Races of Europe] by Carleton S. Coon</ref> The Irano-Afghan type was classified as belonging to the greater [[Caucasian race|Caucasian]] race. It was variously associated with either the [[Nordic race|Nordic]] subtype or the [[Mediterranean race|Mediterranean]] subtype, depending on the authority consulted.

==Physiognomy==
[[Carleton S. Coon]] in his ''[[The Races of Europe (1939 book)|The Races of Europe]]'' classifies the ''Indo-Afghans'' and ''Irano-Afghans'' as Nordic, describing them as being long-faced, high-headed and leptorrhine (having long and narrow noses). [[Bertil Lundman]] by contrast postulates an "Iranid" subtype of his "Eastern Mediterranean" race. [[Earnest Hooton]] in 1946 describes the "Iranian Plateau type" as distinct from the [[Atlanto-Mediterranean]] one:
{{quote|particularly in its long, high-bridged, and boldly jutting nasal promontory. It has the same huge dolichocephalic head and massive, usually long face. The great nose may be either straight or convex, more often the latter.<ref name="hooton1">{{cite web |url=http://dienekes.awardspace.com/texts/hootonmed/ |title=Earnest Hooton on the Mediterranean Subrace (from E. A. Hooton, Up from the Ape, 1946) |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>}}

According to Renato Biasutti the type was defined by:
{{quote|Brunet-white color, very dark hair and eyes, abundant pilosity; medium stature (165), slim body; very long (74) and high head with prominent occiput; long face; large and high nose with root at the level of the forehead, straight or convex spine, strongly curved nostrils (64); full lips, robust chin.<ref name="biasutti">{{cite web|url=http://dienekes.110mb.com/texts/biasutticaucasoid/ |last=Biasutti |first=Renato |title=Renato Biasutti on Caucasoid Subraces: from Le Razze e i popoli della terra |pages=409–410 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511091339/http://dienekes.110mb.com/texts/biasutticaucasoid/ |archivedate=2012-05-11 |df= }}</ref>}}

[[John Lawrence Angel]] following Coon in 1971 discusses a "Nordic-Iranian type" in the following terms:
{{quote|D1 lies between Anglo-Saxon and Keltic area norms, and D2 is the earlier pre-Bronze Age Corded form which Coon identifies. Type D3, lighter and more hawk-nosed, is transitional to the Mediterranean type B4 and to type D4 (Iranian), which is the Proto-Iranian of Vallois, Irano-Afghan of others, and Proto-Nordic of Krogman, and which is more linear and more rugged than D3 and has a more tilted chewing plane, more [[aquiline nose|nasal convexity]], and deeper occiput. Type D5 approximates Coon's Danubian-Halstatt and successor Central European forms.<ref>J. Lawrence Angel, ''The people of Lerna; analysis of a prehistoric Aegean population'', Princeton, N.J., American School of Classical Studies at Athens, 1971, pp. 36–38 [http://dienekes.awardspace.com/texts/angeltypes/]</ref>}}

